				<td valign="bottom"><img src="/english/images/bbs_line.gif"></td>
                <td align="left" style="padding:5 10" width="388"><font class="title01">Pantech Boosts Global Reach with Award of GSM License  in China</font> </td>
				<td valign="bottom"><img src="/english/images/bbs_line.gif"></td>
                <td width="100" align="center">Mar.31,2005</td>
              </tr>
			  <tr class="bbs05"> 
                <td height="1" colspan="5"><img src="/english/images/blank.gif"></td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="bbs03"> 
                <td colspan="2" height="21" align="center">&nbsp;</td>
                <td colspan="3" align="left" style="padding:5 10">SEOUL, March 31, 2005 - Pantech, one of the world’s leading mobile communications groups - comprised of Pantech&Curitel Inc., Pantech Co., Ltd. and Pantech C&I Inc. - has just become the first foreign company to be awarded a GSM license in China following recent changes in Chinese mobile licensing policy. <br>
<br>
Pantech secured a license for the sale of CDMA handsets in the Chinese market in November 2004. Subsequently, regulations governing the approval of GSM license applications in China were revised earlier this year, allowing Pantech to successfully apply for a GSM license. <br>
<br>
Sung-Kyu Lee, President & CEO, Pantech Co., Ltd., said: “We are aware that China is a fiercely competitive field for any handset producer. However, we are convinced that we can deliver affordable, premium, cutting edge mobile phones that will have significant value for consumers in China.” <br>
<br>
“We are committed to dramatically building up our sales and marketing force in China to support the projected demand in this market. We already have the products and the technology. Our focus now is put in place the infrastructure to bring our state of the art products to the Chinese population,” said Mr. Lee. <br>
<br>
The mobile phone market in China has grown significantly in recent years, with unit sales of 64 million in 2004. The market is expected to grow to 100 million units per annum in 2/3 years’ time. Given that GSM phones account for over 80% of the Chinese handset market, the award of the new license will strengthen Pantech’s position in China.<br>
<br>
The Pantech brand was officially introduced to China at the PT/EXPO COMM trade show in October 2004. However, in the three years up to 2004, Pantech supplied 5.5 million handsets to the Chinese market. <br>
<br>
<br>
In September 2003, Pantech formed a joint venture with Dalian city, near Beijing - called Dalian Daxian-Pantech Communication Co., Ltd. - to operate a manufacturing facility, with the capacity to produce four million handsets annually.<br>
<br>
The award of the GSM license means that Pantech will be targeting many of its latest models at the Chinese market, including the Power Pixel Series phones - the PG-3000 and the GF-500. <br>
<br>
The PG-3000 is a slim and slider model, with an extraordinary array of functionality, including a 1.3 mega pixel CMOS camera that also works like a semi-camcorder, supporting MJPEG files. <br>
<br>
Meanwhile, the GF500 also contains a 1.3 mega pixel camera and internal flash - along with a white light emitting diode (LED) panel on top - as well as wide ranging multimedia support capability. <br>
<br>
“In the past, we were focused on selling handsets on an original-design-manufacturer (ODM) basis. Now we have licenses to sell our own brand of both CDMA and GSM handsets in China, typically rendering higher margins than ODM products. This is in line with our strategy to increase sales under our own brand globally,” said Mr. Lee.<br>
</td>
              </tr>
